Live streams and lights
big screens don't happen

00:01:36.360 --> 00:01:37.660
by themselves.

00:01:37.660 --> 00:01:39.670
So thanks to my colleagues
for making things happen.

00:01:39.670 --> 00:01:40.970
All right.

00:01:40.970 --> 00:01:45.330
So here on Capitol Hill,
three buildings are part

00:01:45.330 --> 00:01:47.080
of the Library of Congress.

00:01:47.080 --> 00:01:50.530
And they are named for three
of our founding fathers.

00:01:50.530 --> 00:01:53.700
The building that we're in
this morning is the James

00:01:53.700 --> 00:01:55.000
Madison building.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:59.210
And for those of you who came in
downstairs on our first floor,

00:01:59.210 --> 00:02:01.970
if you had looked
over to your left,

00:02:01.970 --> 00:02:04.870
you would have seen a
statue of James Madison.

00:02:04.870 --> 00:02:08.380
And you if you'd walked into the
room, you could have read some

00:02:08.380 --> 00:02:10.920
of his quotes on the walls.

00:02:10.920 --> 00:02:12.220
They're engraved down there.

00:02:12.220 --> 00:02:15.220
And there's one that sort
of speaks to the Library

00:02:15.220 --> 00:02:18.790
of Congress and to cultural
institutions like the library.

00:02:18.790 --> 00:02:21.800
And frankly, I think it sort
of speaks to today's program.

00:02:21.800 --> 00:02:24.910
So I'm going to paraphrase
it a little bit for you.

00:02:24.910 --> 00:02:31.340
It reads, learned institutions
ought to be favorite objects

00:02:31.340 --> 00:02:33.350
with every free people.

00:02:33.350 --> 00:02:36.340
They throw light
over the public mind.

00:02:36.340 --> 00:02:38.760
I love that.

00:02:38.760 --> 00:02:42.940
They throw light
over the public mind.

00:02:42.940 --> 00:02:45.110
Even as Kathy and Alan

00:02:45.110 --> 00:02:48.430
and I were first discussing
this program last summer

00:02:48.430 --> 00:02:51.050
at the ALA conference,
I had a hunch

00:02:51.050 --> 00:02:54.560
that this would be a
light-throwing event.

00:02:54.560 --> 00:02:58.840
So now, I'm about to introduce
this morning's panel moderator.

00:02:58.840 --> 00:03:02.450
But for the transition to make
any sense, you all will need

00:03:02.450 --> 00:03:05.640
to know that when I described
the library to people

00:03:05.640 --> 00:03:08.970
who do not know much
about it, I often talk

00:03:08.970 --> 00:03:12.610
about it being a place
that sparks ideas.

00:03:12.610 --> 00:03:17.470
The primary sources in the
collections: my colleagues,

00:03:17.470 --> 00:03:19.860
the architecture of the
Thomas Jefferson building.

00:03:19.860 --> 00:03:24.100
They all inspire creativity,
and they help us learn

00:03:24.100 --> 00:03:26.780
and imagine possibilities.

00:03:28.220 --> 00:03:31.780
Okay. So a minute ago, we were
talking about throwing light,

00:03:31.780 --> 00:03:34.230
and I've just mentioned sparks.

00:03:34.230 --> 00:03:37.290
So when Kathy asked me if I
would introduce our moderator,

00:03:37.290 --> 00:03:39.850
naturally, I did a
little research about her.

00:03:39.850 --> 00:03:44.110
And immediately, I
thought, wow, serendipity.

00:03:44.110 --> 00:03:45.810
This author is perfect.

00:03:45.810 --> 00:03:49.620
Her website has a fabulous URL.

00:03:49.620 --> 00:03:55.350
This morning's moderator is
Linda Sue Park, L.S. Park.

00:03:55.350 --> 00:03:58.820
And if you go to her website,

00:03:58.820 --> 00:04:03.770
you'll find that
the URL, lspark.

00:04:06.110 --> 00:04:07.980
Huh! Magic.

00:04:07.980 --> 00:04:11.060
Linda was born in
Urbana, Illinois.

00:04:11.060 --> 00:04:14.210
She grew up outside of Chicago
and earned her bachelor's degree

00:04:14.210 --> 00:04:16.060
at Stanford University.

00:04:16.060 --> 00:04:19.280
She is a Newberry medalist and
the author of numerous novels,

00:04:19.280 --> 00:04:22.500
picture books, and poetry
collections for children.

00:04:22.500 --> 00:04:26.530
Her work often uses historical
settings and innovative forms

00:04:26.530 --> 00:04:29.810
to expand young readers'
sense of possibility.

00:04:29.810 --> 00:04:33.880
Her poetry collection,
Tap Dancing on the Roof,

00:04:33.880 --> 00:04:39.670
utilizes a Korean syllabic verse
form to bring surprise and humor

00:04:39.670 --> 00:04:42.130
to everyday moments and objects.

00:04:42.130 --> 00:04:46.120
Her novels for teenage
readers include A Single Shard,

00:04:46.120 --> 00:04:50.290
When My Name Was Keoko,
and A Long Walk to Water,

00:04:50.290 --> 00:04:52.120
based on a true story.

00:04:52.120 --> 00:04:55.570
Her picture books include,
The Firekeeper's Son,

00:04:55.570 --> 00:05:00.220
illustrated by Julie
Downing, and Bee-bim Bop,

00:05:00.220 --> 00:05:02.630
illustrated by Ho Baek Lee.

00:05:02.630 --> 00:05:05.030
She lives with her family
in Rochester, New York.

00:05:05.030 --> 00:05:09.160
And I have the feeling
she is just who we need

00:05:09.160 --> 00:05:12.390
to start throwing some light
on our program this morning.

00:05:12.390 --> 00:05:15.510
Please join me in
welcoming Linda Sue Park.

00:05:15.510 --> 00:05:25.200
[ Applause ]

00:05:25.200 --> 00:05:26.740
&gt;&gt; Linda Sue Park: Good morning.

00:05:26.740 --> 00:05:30.680
I am already having so much fun.

00:05:30.680 --> 00:05:32.660
I'd like to thank the
Library of Congress,

00:05:32.660 --> 00:05:35.680
and We Need Diverse Books, of
course, and especially Ellen O

00:05:35.680 --> 00:05:38.340
and Caroline Richman
and Kathy Weinberg,

00:05:38.340 --> 00:05:42.040
the Walter Awards judging panel,
and all of you for being here,

00:05:42.040 --> 00:05:44.810
including those of you online.

00:05:44.810 --> 00:05:49.180
I serve on the advisory board
of We Need Diverse Books.

00:05:49.180 --> 00:05:51.550
And I'm just so thrilled
that they asked me

00:05:51.550 --> 00:05:53.990
to be the moderator
of today's symposium.

00:05:53.990 --> 00:05:57.580
So we have the power of books.

00:05:57.580 --> 00:06:01.120
And I'm guessing that if you are
in this room, you have a story

00:06:01.120 --> 00:06:03.930
or two about the power of books.

00:06:03.930 --> 00:06:06.260
A couple of quick ones of mine.

00:06:06.260 --> 00:06:09.110
My daughter is named
after a character in one

00:06:09.110 --> 00:06:11.780
of Charlotte [inaudible] books.

00:06:11.780 --> 00:06:16.510
Many years ago, I moved to
Brooklyn because of A Tree Grows

00:06:16.510 --> 00:06:22.430
in Brooklyn, but
perhaps most important,

00:06:22.430 --> 00:06:25.930
I survived a childhood
of being different,

00:06:25.930 --> 00:06:29.790
in part because of the
strength books gave me.

00:06:29.790 --> 00:06:33.410
This morning, I am delighted
to introduce the three winners

00:06:33.410 --> 00:06:38.050
of the Walter Honor Awards,
whose work turns the power

00:06:38.050 --> 00:06:40.920
of books into a juggernaut.

00:06:42.180 --> 00:06:47.060
Margarita Engle is the national
young people's poet laureate

00:06:47.060 --> 00:06:50.780
and the first Latina
to receive that honor.

00:06:50.780 --> 00:06:53.750
She is the Cuban-American
recipient of many awards

00:06:53.750 --> 00:06:56.980
for her verse novels,
including a Newbery honor

00:06:56.980 --> 00:07:00.240
for The Surrender Tree,
a PEN literary award

00:07:00.240 --> 00:07:02.470
for The Lightning
Dreamer, a Pura Belpre

00:07:02.470 --> 00:07:05.930
and a previous Walter
honor for Enchanted Air.

00:07:05.930 --> 00:07:07.250
And I just decided
that was enough.

00:07:07.250 --> 00:07:12.040
I couldn't keep listing
the rest of them.

00:07:12.040 --> 00:07:15.530
Most recently, she was named by
the United States board of books

00:07:15.530 --> 00:07:17.680
for young people
as the US nominee

00:07:17.680 --> 00:07:21.570
for the 2018 Astrid
Lindgren Memorial award,

00:07:21.570 --> 00:07:23.850
and she is the author
of Forest World,

00:07:23.850 --> 00:07:26.730
the 2018 Walter honor title

00:07:26.730 --> 00:07:30.510
for younger readers,
Margarita Engle.

00:07:30.510 --> 00:07:41.620
[ Applause ]

00:07:41.620 --> 00:07:43.130
&gt;&gt; Mitali Perkins' novels

00:07:43.130 --> 00:07:45.530
for young readers
include Rickshaw Girl,

00:07:45.530 --> 00:07:49.330
a New York public library top
100 book, and Bamboo People,

00:07:49.330 --> 00:07:51.700
an ALA top 10 [inaudible] novel.

00:07:51.700 --> 00:07:54.470
Mitali was born in Kolkata,
India, and has lived

00:07:54.470 --> 00:07:57.650
in Bangladesh, India,
England, Thailand,

00:07:57.650 --> 00:08:00.720
Mexico, Cameroon and Ghana.

00:08:00.720 --> 00:08:02.870
She currently resides
in San Francisco

00:08:02.870 --> 00:08:07.640
where she is a lecturer at St.
Mary's College of California.

00:08:07.640 --> 00:08:10.740
She is the author of You
Bring the Distant Near,

00:08:10.740 --> 00:08:15.320
a 2018 Walter honor
book for older readers.

00:08:15.320 --> 00:08:16.620
Mitali, where's Mitali?

00:08:16.620 --> 00:08:18.420
There she is.

00:08:18.420 --> 00:08:27.070
[ Applause ]

00:08:27.070 --> 00:08:32.240
Francisco X. Stork is the author
of Marcelo in the Real World,

00:08:32.240 --> 00:08:35.070
winner of the Schneider
family book award for teens,

00:08:35.070 --> 00:08:38.140
and Once Upon a World,
and the, oh, sorry,

00:08:38.140 --> 00:08:40.970
and the Once Upon a World
award, also the author

00:08:40.970 --> 00:08:43.540
of The Last Summer of
the Death Warriors,

00:08:43.540 --> 00:08:47.270
on the YALSA Best Fiction
for Teens list and winner

00:08:47.270 --> 00:08:49.530
of the Amelia Elizabeth
Waldon Award.

00:08:49.530 --> 00:08:54.580
He lives outside Boston, and he
is the author of Disappeared,

00:08:54.580 --> 00:08:59.510
a 2018 Walter Honor
book for older readers.

00:08:59.510 --> 00:09:12.610
[ Applause ]

00:09:12.610 --> 00:09:21.640
Okay. We're going to start
with the panelists as readers.

00:09:21.640 --> 00:09:24.850
So my first question is, I'd
like to ask them to think back

00:09:24.850 --> 00:09:28.050
to their childhoods and where
did your books come from.

00:09:28.050 --> 00:09:31.070
Were you public school
library attendees?

00:09:31.070 --> 00:09:32.370
Was it school?

00:09:32.370 --> 00:09:33.670
Was it your parents?

00:09:33.670 --> 00:09:37.450
How did you have access
to books when you young?

00:09:37.450 --> 00:09:38.750
So Margarita, go ahead.

00:09:38.750 --> 00:09:41.820
&gt;&gt; Margarita Engle: For me,
it was the public library,

00:09:41.820 --> 00:09:45.790
the Arroyo Seco branch
in Northeast Los Angeles.

00:09:45.790 --> 00:09:49.420
And I would go every
Saturday and get a stack.

00:09:49.420 --> 00:09:53.760
But I have to say that
I read more adult books

00:09:53.760 --> 00:09:55.880
than children's books.

00:09:55.880 --> 00:09:59.000
That's because I wanted
international books.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:01.380
I wanted books about
other countries.

00:10:01.380 --> 00:10:05.000
And at that time,
there weren't books

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:07.800
about other countries
for children.

00:10:07.800 --> 00:10:11.240
So I would go in the
adult travel section,

00:10:11.240 --> 00:10:12.750
which was illegal.

00:10:12.750 --> 00:10:15.550
The librarians would
chase me away.

00:10:17.160 --> 00:10:21.470
They thought I was supposed to
stay in the children's section.

00:10:21.470 --> 00:10:25.730
But I would get anything
about geography and travel

00:10:25.730 --> 00:10:28.150
in other countries
that I could find.

00:10:28.150 --> 00:10:29.450
&gt;&gt; Linda Sue Park: Wonderful.

00:10:29.450 --> 00:10:30.750
Mitali.

00:10:30.750 --> 00:10:32.050
&gt;&gt; Mitali Perkins: Yes,

00:10:32.050 --> 00:10:34.150
definitely the public
library in Flushing, Queens.

00:10:34.150 --> 00:10:37.110
We immigrated -- Yes, Flushing!

00:10:38.790 --> 00:10:43.730
So we immigrated there when I
was seven and come from a family

00:10:43.730 --> 00:10:45.510
that is immigrant and refugee.

00:10:45.510 --> 00:10:49.860
My parents lost everything
in the war, left Bangladesh,

00:10:49.860 --> 00:10:52.130
arrived in Kolkata, and then
when we came to the states,

00:10:52.130 --> 00:10:54.740
like a lot of immigrant
families, we had very little.

00:10:54.740 --> 00:10:56.130
So no books in the home.

00:10:56.130 --> 00:10:58.100
But my sister one day
-- I have two sisters,

00:10:58.100 --> 00:10:59.970
Sonali, Rupali and Mitali.

00:10:59.970 --> 00:11:03.010
We all speak Bengali.

00:11:03.010 --> 00:11:06.150
Sonali took me by the hand and
said I have a surprise for you

00:11:06.150 --> 00:11:08.490
because she knew I was a
reader already, took me down.

00:11:08.490 --> 00:11:11.800
We walked ten blocks
to the Flushing branch.

00:11:11.800 --> 00:11:14.330
And when I walked in, she said,
you can take seven books home.

00:11:14.330 --> 00:11:18.210
And I was just is
this Ali Baba's cave.

00:11:18.210 --> 00:11:19.510
What has happened?

00:11:19.510 --> 00:11:22.440
So that was where
I started reading.

00:11:22.440 --> 00:11:24.110
&gt;&gt; Francisco X. Stork:
I grew up in Mexico.

00:11:24.110 --> 00:11:26.220
My mother was a single mother.

00:11:26.220 --> 00:11:28.120
So we lived in my
grandfather's house.

00:11:28.120 --> 00:11:32.020
And there was just one
bookcase in his bedroom.

00:11:32.020 --> 00:11:34.370
It was like one of those
old kind of glass things.

00:11:34.370 --> 00:11:36.170
And I knew where the
key was hidden, so.

00:11:36.170 --> 00:11:38.600
And he had this set of volume.

00:11:38.600 --> 00:11:41.530
I think it was like 20 volumes
called [foreign language

00:11:41.530 --> 00:11:43.880
spoken], which was like
treasures for youth.

00:11:43.880 --> 00:11:48.630
And it was like a compilation
of fiction, nonfiction,

00:11:48.630 --> 00:11:50.280
you know, stories of science.

00:11:50.280 --> 00:11:55.100
You could learn a language if
you read those things carefully.

00:11:55.100 --> 00:11:58.340
So that's how I -- I
went through those books,

00:11:58.340 --> 00:12:04.930
and I don't think I saw a
library until we moved to Texas

00:12:04.930 --> 00:12:06.230
when I was nine years old.

00:12:06.230 --> 00:12:07.530
&gt;&gt; Linda Sue Park:
I think about that.

00:12:07.530 --> 00:12:08.870
I think about all the
places in the world.

00:12:08.870 --> 00:12:11.570
And even in our country, where
young people don't have access

00:12:11.570 --> 00:12:17.130
to a library, how do
they live, you know?

00:12:17.130 --> 00:12:19.450
So, I mean, that's
really interesting.

00:12:19.450 --> 00:12:22.420
Okay. Could you talk
about the first time?

00:12:22.420 --> 00:12:24.420
And it may not have been in your
childhood, but the first time

00:12:24.420 --> 00:12:28.250
that you felt seen in a book
or heard in a book, right.

00:12:28.250 --> 00:12:32.030
So why don't we start at
the other end this time.

00:12:32.030 --> 00:12:33.330
Yeah.

00:12:33.330 --> 00:12:34.630
&gt;&gt; Francisco X. Stork: You know,
I grew up with this identity

00:12:34.630 --> 00:12:41.310
of being Mexican
for a long time.

00:12:41.310 --> 00:12:46.450
I didn't become an American
citizen till I was 26.

00:12:46.450 --> 00:12:51.580
So it really the authors
from Latin America

00:12:51.580 --> 00:12:54.580
that I just grew up with.

00:12:54.580 --> 00:12:59.150
It was only when I was
in college and I realized

00:12:59.150 --> 00:13:04.090
that now I had lived, you know,
15 years in the United States

00:13:04.090 --> 00:13:07.340
and I had gone through learning
a new language and, you know,

00:13:07.340 --> 00:13:10.400
getting paddled for speaking
Spanish in the playground

00:13:10.400 --> 00:13:12.950
and getting rejected
by the beautiful Becky

00:13:12.950 --> 00:13:16.240
because I was Mexican.

00:13:16.240 --> 00:13:17.740
But, you know, there
were certain things

00:13:17.740 --> 00:13:20.450
that were a little bit
different than Mexicans.

00:13:20.450 --> 00:13:22.010
And I began to acquire
that identity.

00:13:22.010 --> 00:13:25.860
And I think it was like [foreign
language spoken], where I kind

00:13:25.860 --> 00:13:30.040
of saw, you know, this
possibility of this, yeah,

00:13:30.040 --> 00:13:35.320
this kind of looks a
little bit more like me.

00:13:35.320 --> 00:13:36.620
&gt;&gt; Linda Sue Park: Okay, Mitali.

00:13:36.620 --> 00:13:37.920
&gt;&gt; Mitali Perkins: Yeah.

00:13:37.920 --> 00:13:39.250
I wanted books because I
didn't like being seen.

00:13:39.250 --> 00:13:41.710
I moved to California when
I was in seventh grade,

00:13:41.710 --> 00:13:44.150
and I was the only kid of
color in the whole school.

00:13:44.150 --> 00:13:46.920
And I was the only kid not born
in the USA in the whole school.

00:13:46.920 --> 00:13:51.420
So books for me were a way
to see and hear other lives.

00:13:51.420 --> 00:13:54.270
So at school, I was doing
that code switching dance.

00:13:54.270 --> 00:13:56.500
At school, I was using
my curling iron to try

00:13:56.500 --> 00:13:59.520
to transform myself into
Farrah Fawcett every morning,

00:13:59.520 --> 00:14:02.650
that I could miraculously look

00:14:02.650 --> 00:14:04.010
like everyone else,
which I never did.

00:14:04.010 --> 00:14:07.130
So I think for me, it was
that marvelous ability

00:14:07.130 --> 00:14:10.470
that books give us to
see and hear other lives

00:14:10.470 --> 00:14:13.480
and imagine other lives, which
I feel is a huge advantage

00:14:13.480 --> 00:14:17.000
that we get when we have
to cross borders to read.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:20.240
And so, I was learning to become
fluent in imagining other lives.

00:14:20.240 --> 00:14:23.470
And I think that's how
books served me well.

00:14:24.740 --> 00:14:26.800
&gt;&gt; Margarita Engle: I was the
only Cuban-American growing

00:14:26.800 --> 00:14:29.420
up in a Mexican American
neighborhood.

00:14:29.420 --> 00:14:33.760
And as much as I loved
the poetry of Mexico,

00:14:33.760 --> 00:14:38.070
especially [foreign word
spoken], my mother introduced me

00:14:38.070 --> 00:14:42.310
to [foreign word spoken]
and I love all the poets

00:14:42.310 --> 00:14:47.370
of Latin America and Spain, but
especially the generation of 27

00:14:47.370 --> 00:14:53.300
from Spain, who were, you
know, resisting the oppression.

00:14:53.300 --> 00:14:57.060
And so, poetry was
very influential.

00:14:57.060 --> 00:15:00.590
But I have to say, as far
as being seen in a book,

00:15:00.590 --> 00:15:06.360
I was 50 something when I
read Alma Flor Ada's memoir,

00:15:06.360 --> 00:15:09.790
Under the Royal Palms, and that
would be the first time I read

00:15:09.790 --> 00:15:15.680
something written
specifically about Cuba.

00:15:15.680 --> 00:15:16.980
&gt;&gt; Linda Sue Park: Right.

00:15:16.980 --> 00:15:19.570
So we're here to make sure no
one else ever, no child ever has

00:15:19.570 --> 00:15:20.870
to wait that long again, right.

00:15:20.870 --> 00:15:22.380
&gt;&gt; Yeah, that's right.

00:15:22.380 --> 00:15:24.040
&gt;&gt; Linda Sue Park: You
know, when I was growing up,

00:15:24.040 --> 00:15:27.530
I have a very clear memory of
the first Asians I ever saw

00:15:27.530 --> 00:15:31.970
in a book, which was that
Five Chinese Brothers book.

00:15:31.970 --> 00:15:34.430
Yeah. Okay, right.

00:15:34.430 --> 00:15:35.730
Let's move on.

00:15:35.730 --> 00:15:38.490
All right.

00:15:38.490 --> 00:15:44.470
Okay. Do you have either a book
or books or an author or authors

00:15:44.470 --> 00:15:46.590
who are your greatest influence

00:15:46.590 --> 00:15:49.880
or your greatest
inspiration, and why is that?

00:15:49.880 --> 00:15:52.790
Is it because of their
craft, subject matter, theme?

00:15:52.790 --> 00:15:56.330
I mean, do you have, you know,
authors that you just sort

00:15:56.330 --> 00:15:58.050
of hold up as your light?

00:15:58.050 --> 00:16:00.510
Mitali, we'll start
with you this time.

00:16:00.510 --> 00:16:02.170
&gt;&gt; Mitali Perkins: I just
finished my annual reread

00:16:02.170 --> 00:16:03.470
of Little Women again.

00:16:03.470 --> 00:16:08.860
And I think I loved Jo much, Jo
March, because she was living

00:16:08.860 --> 00:16:12.850
in 19th century Concord,
Massachusetts, and I living

00:16:12.850 --> 00:16:15.730
in a traditional
middle-class Bengali home.

00:16:15.730 --> 00:16:19.990
But in terms of the pressure
she faced not to use writing

00:16:19.990 --> 00:16:23.260
as a way to make money,
if you reread that book,

00:16:23.260 --> 00:16:26.160
there's a strong theme in there
about how she chose her vocation

00:16:26.160 --> 00:16:28.430
as a writer, despite
all the pressures.

00:16:28.430 --> 00:16:30.480
And any of you from South
Asian backgrounds know

00:16:30.480 --> 00:16:32.420
that we basically
had three options:

00:16:32.420 --> 00:16:34.380
engineer, doctor and engineer.

00:16:34.380 --> 00:16:37.910
Those were our three
options vocationally.

00:16:37.910 --> 00:16:40.810
So yeah. So she pushed
those boundaries,

00:16:40.810 --> 00:16:43.520
and she loved her sisters,
and she loved her writing.

00:16:43.520 --> 00:16:44.960
For her, her writing
was something

00:16:44.960 --> 00:16:46.580
that she was never
going to give up on.

00:16:46.580 --> 00:16:48.270
And that's how I felt
about my writing,

00:16:48.270 --> 00:16:49.910
despite all of that pressure.

00:16:49.910 --> 00:16:54.850
A refined Bengali woman in that
time did not write for money.

00:16:54.850 --> 00:16:56.490
We wrote for beauty.

00:16:56.490 --> 00:16:59.400
And so, I think when Jo said no,
I'm going to make money on this

00:16:59.400 --> 00:17:00.980
and I'm going to be
independent, I loved her,

00:17:00.980 --> 00:17:02.570
and I still love her for that.

00:17:02.570 --> 00:17:03.870
&gt;&gt; Linda Sue Park: Nice, nice.

00:17:03.870 --> 00:17:05.170
So Francisco.

00:17:05.170 --> 00:17:06.470
&gt;&gt; Francisco X. Stork:
I guess, you know,

00:17:06.470 --> 00:17:08.150
one of my favorite authors
is Flannery O'Connor,

00:17:08.150 --> 00:17:09.450
a southern author.

00:17:09.450 --> 00:17:11.410
And I think I was more her life.

00:17:11.410 --> 00:17:13.520
You know, she only
wrote two novels

00:17:13.520 --> 00:17:16.830
and two [inaudible]
short stories.

00:17:16.830 --> 00:17:18.650
But she was a person of faith.

00:17:18.650 --> 00:17:22.370
And her works are
infused with that faith,

00:17:22.370 --> 00:17:25.120
but you'd never know it, you
know, if you read her work.

00:17:25.120 --> 00:17:28.930
In fact, in many cases, you'd
think like the opposite,

00:17:28.930 --> 00:17:34.280
you know, just because they're
so undidactic and so powerful.

00:17:34.280 --> 00:17:37.950
So you read her books, and
then you put it down and like,

00:17:37.950 --> 00:17:39.830
you know, what the
hell just happened.

00:17:39.830 --> 00:17:43.310
And you begin -- And
a little while later,

00:17:43.310 --> 00:17:46.270
you begin to like notice things
that you didn't notice before.

00:17:46.270 --> 00:17:51.210
And I think that the ability
to see things differently is

00:17:51.210 --> 00:17:56.040
that power that she gave
me and that I would hope

00:17:56.040 --> 00:17:57.590
to emulate in my writing.

00:17:57.590 --> 00:17:58.890
&gt;&gt; Mitali Perkins: And
that's why I'm a Francisco X.

00:17:58.890 --> 00:18:00.190
Stork fan.

00:18:00.190 --> 00:18:01.500
Exactly as you described
Flannery O'Connor is how I would

00:18:01.500 --> 00:18:02.800
describe your work.

00:18:02.800 --> 00:18:04.390
&gt;&gt; Linda Sue Park: Nice, yeah.

00:18:04.390 --> 00:18:05.690
Margarita.

00:18:05.690 --> 00:18:06.990
&gt;&gt; Margarita Engle: You know,

00:18:06.990 --> 00:18:11.300
I'm going to say Marilyn
Nelson's Carver influenced me

00:18:11.300 --> 00:18:13.060
because it was the first time --

00:18:13.060 --> 00:18:17.130
And again, 50 something
when I read it.

00:18:17.130 --> 00:18:22.570
But it was the first time
I read a verse biography

00:18:22.570 --> 00:18:26.220
about someone who'd been
neglected by history.

00:18:26.220 --> 00:18:30.360
And that's something I've
really strived to do is to write

00:18:30.360 --> 00:18:33.430
about people who've
been forgotten and left

00:18:33.430 --> 00:18:34.730
out of the history books.

00:18:34.730 --> 00:18:38.970
And Carver has not been left out
as much as some of the people

00:18:38.970 --> 00:18:41.660
that I've felt inspired
to write about.

00:18:41.660 --> 00:18:44.490
But it was just such
a beautiful thing

00:18:44.490 --> 00:18:52.140
that she did doing a biography
in verse instead of in the kind

00:18:52.140 --> 00:18:56.040
of formal nonfiction
with footnotes

00:18:56.040 --> 00:19:02.270
that a child might not
feel invited and welcomed

00:19:02.270 --> 00:19:07.490
to open the pages and go,
ah, this was written for me.

00:19:07.490 --> 00:19:08.790
&gt;&gt; Linda Sue Park: Have
you ever told Marilyn that?

00:19:08.790 --> 00:19:10.090
&gt;&gt; Margarita Engle:
No, I haven't.

00:19:10.090 --> 00:19:11.390
Maybe she'll she this.

00:19:11.390 --> 00:19:12.690
&gt;&gt; Linda Sue Park: If
you don't know this book,

00:19:12.690 --> 00:19:13.990
I have a special
affection for this book

00:19:13.990 --> 00:19:15.290
because it was an
honor book the year

00:19:15.290 --> 00:19:16.590
that A Single Shard
won the Newbery.

00:19:16.590 --> 00:19:17.890
And it's a heroic
crown of sonnets.

00:19:17.890 --> 00:19:20.990
And it's an incredibly complex
form and difficult to write,

00:19:20.990 --> 00:19:22.860
and it ends within acrostic.

00:19:22.860 --> 00:19:25.580
I mean, it will blow your mind.

00:19:25.580 --> 00:19:26.880
So yeah.

00:19:26.880 --> 00:19:28.850
&gt;&gt; Margarita Engle: And it
comes across very simple

00:19:28.850 --> 00:19:31.690
and [inaudible] understand
for a child reading.

00:19:31.690 --> 00:19:32.990
&gt;&gt; Linda Sue Park: Yeah.

00:19:32.990 --> 00:19:34.290
It's an amazing book.

00:19:34.290 --> 00:19:37.460
Okay. Now, we're going to move
on to our panelists as writers.

00:19:37.460 --> 00:19:41.500
And it was very interesting to
receive these books and to go

00:19:41.500 --> 00:19:44.760
through them and to read them in
preparation for this symposium.

00:19:44.760 --> 00:19:47.700
And immediately, what I noticed
first, the writer part of me,

00:19:47.700 --> 00:19:51.190
is that all three of
them chose to use more

00:19:51.190 --> 00:19:52.960
than one viewpoint, okay.

00:19:52.960 --> 00:19:56.360
So we have alternating chapters
or sections in all three books.

00:19:56.360 --> 00:19:58.740
So I thought that was a really
interesting thing they have

00:19:58.740 --> 00:20:00.040
in common.

00:20:00.040 --> 00:20:02.920
And so, I'd like you to tell us
about your multiple characters

00:20:02.920 --> 00:20:05.440
and why you chose them
to be the ones to be seen

00:20:05.440 --> 00:20:07.170
and heard in your book.

00:20:07.170 --> 00:20:08.980
So we'll go with
Margarita this time.

00:20:08.980 --> 00:20:12.530
&gt;&gt; Margarita Engle: Well,
Forest World is an eco-adventure

00:20:12.530 --> 00:20:16.360
about biodiversity and
wilderness preservation in Cuba,

00:20:16.360 --> 00:20:22.030
but it's also a family
reunification story set in 2015

00:20:22.030 --> 00:20:25.140
when President Obama had
initiated the peacemaking

00:20:25.140 --> 00:20:27.330
process between the US and Cuba.

00:20:27.330 --> 00:20:30.750
And I felt so excited.

00:20:30.750 --> 00:20:34.080
And the only way I felt

00:20:34.080 --> 00:20:37.140
like I could show this
peacemaking process was

00:20:37.140 --> 00:20:41.730
by two children, siblings, who'd
never met each other before.

00:20:41.730 --> 00:20:44.690
And that is very
common where one grows

00:20:44.690 --> 00:20:46.970
up in Miami and one in Cuba.

00:20:46.970 --> 00:20:50.400
And so, even though I've
heard people say they don't

00:20:50.400 --> 00:20:54.060
like readings, I'm going
to take just a minute

00:20:54.060 --> 00:20:58.760
to read one very short
poem in the sister's voice.

00:20:58.760 --> 00:21:02.380
She's grown up in a
rural area in Cuban.

00:21:02.380 --> 00:21:06.960
The reason I did multiple voices
was to show the difference

00:21:06.960 --> 00:21:08.320
between the US and Cuba.

00:21:08.320 --> 00:21:12.090
Now the American brother who
grew up in Miami, of course,

00:21:12.090 --> 00:21:14.840
lives on his phone and,
you know, everything's

00:21:14.840 --> 00:21:18.480
about Wi-Fi and video games.

00:21:18.480 --> 00:21:21.490
And the girl who's
grown up in Cuba,

00:21:21.490 --> 00:21:24.910
of course doesn't
have access to Wi-Fi.

00:21:24.910 --> 00:21:28.280
In rural Cuba, the fuel
shortage is so severe

00:21:28.280 --> 00:21:29.730
that most people depend

00:21:29.730 --> 00:21:33.780
on horse-drawn vehicles
or hitchhiking.

00:21:33.780 --> 00:21:39.490
And nightfall, the
clip-clop of horse hooves.

00:21:39.490 --> 00:21:43.110
Rhythmic flashes from
dancing fireflies.

00:21:43.110 --> 00:21:46.250
Around each curve
the rising moon.

00:21:46.250 --> 00:21:48.900
Abuelo's long folktales
his stories

00:21:48.900 --> 00:21:52.270
of glow-in-the-dark
dogs and magical horses.

00:21:52.270 --> 00:21:55.550
My brother's fingers
twitch as if he's longing

00:21:55.550 --> 00:21:59.250
to send phone messages
back to his real home.

00:21:59.250 --> 00:22:03.260
What was Mama thinking, forcing
un americano to spend time

00:22:03.260 --> 00:22:09.730
with los Cubanos, sharing
our quiet isolation.

00:22:09.730 --> 00:22:11.030
Thank you.

00:22:11.030 --> 00:22:14.320
&gt;&gt; Linda Sue Park: Who says
people don't like readings?

00:22:14.320 --> 00:22:15.620
I love them.

00:22:15.620 --> 00:22:17.370
I love hearing the
author read, right.

00:22:17.370 --> 00:22:18.680
Okay, yeah.

00:22:18.680 --> 00:22:19.980
Mitali.

00:22:19.980 --> 00:22:21.280
&gt;&gt; Mitali Perkins: Yes.

00:22:21.280 --> 00:22:23.860
So you bring the distant near
as a story of one Bengali family

00:22:23.860 --> 00:22:26.730
who moves to Flushing
Queens from Kolkata, India.

00:22:26.730 --> 00:22:29.920
Gosh, I won't where
I got that idea from?

00:22:29.920 --> 00:22:31.460
It's three generations.

00:22:31.460 --> 00:22:36.260
And so, I have five
voices, but I wanted

00:22:36.260 --> 00:22:39.060
to show how immigration
affects all three

00:22:39.060 --> 00:22:41.340
of those generations
differently.

00:22:41.340 --> 00:22:44.420
So the heroic generation
really is the first one

00:22:44.420 --> 00:22:48.000
that come here seeking really
for the next generation.

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:49.820
They're the ones that
bear the sacrifice,

00:22:49.820 --> 00:22:51.900
the loss and the cost.

00:22:51.900 --> 00:22:53.200
So that's why, in the book,

00:22:53.200 --> 00:22:55.660
the narrative arc
really does belong mostly

00:22:55.660 --> 00:22:57.860
to that first generation,
even though she's

00:22:57.860 --> 00:22:59.630
in the third person voice.

00:22:59.630 --> 00:23:02.710
And then there are the two girls
that are the second generation,

00:23:02.710 --> 00:23:04.520
which was mine, the
code switchers.

00:23:04.520 --> 00:23:07.310
They're learning how to -- They
know about village Bengali life,

00:23:07.310 --> 00:23:10.600
and they know about American
life, in they're learning both.

00:23:10.600 --> 00:23:13.410
And they're gaining more
agency in this culture

00:23:13.410 --> 00:23:16.640
than their parents
have at a very age.

00:23:16.640 --> 00:23:17.940
So that was important to me

00:23:17.940 --> 00:23:19.240
because that's really
my generation.

00:23:19.240 --> 00:23:21.800
And then there's the
third generation, my sons,

00:23:21.800 --> 00:23:26.120
and the question being how
Bengali really are they

00:23:26.120 --> 00:23:29.270
and how do we hold onto that
and how important is that in

00:23:29.270 --> 00:23:31.470
that third generations.

00:23:31.470 --> 00:23:35.750
So people, they'll
identify as Indian, my sons.

00:23:35.750 --> 00:23:38.180
But there are 22 major
languages in India

00:23:38.180 --> 00:23:40.300
and cultures, all
of them distinct.

00:23:40.300 --> 00:23:41.980
So for an Indian
to say I'm Indian,

00:23:41.980 --> 00:23:44.400
it sounds like it
doesn't make any sense.

00:23:44.400 --> 00:23:48.540
So for them, their
Bengali identity,

00:23:48.540 --> 00:23:51.660
really it's getting lost.

00:23:51.660 --> 00:23:54.280
So there's a loss on both
of those generations.

00:23:54.280 --> 00:23:56.760
And it's that middle
generation that straddles.

00:23:56.760 --> 00:23:59.590
So I wanted to see all of
those three generations

00:23:59.590 --> 00:24:02.510
and how immigration
affects that.

00:24:02.510 --> 00:24:03.810
&gt;&gt; Francisco X. Stork:

00:24:03.810 --> 00:24:05.690
So Disappeared has
two main characters.

00:24:05.690 --> 00:24:10.000
Sarah is a young
journalist in Juarez, Mexico,

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:11.670
and she's investigating
the disappearance

00:24:11.670 --> 00:24:13.430
of so many women
during the time,

00:24:13.430 --> 00:24:15.770
during a certain period of time.

00:24:15.770 --> 00:24:19.570
And her brother, Emiliano,
is kind of a real go getter.

00:24:19.570 --> 00:24:24.680
You know, he's a soccer star
or football I should say,

00:24:24.680 --> 00:24:31.680
and has this little
business, a craft business.

00:24:31.680 --> 00:24:35.910
And there really like -- The
reason I had like two voices is

00:24:35.910 --> 00:24:37.710
because there were kind
of like two journeys.

00:24:37.710 --> 00:24:40.220
One of them is sort of
like the journey of kind

00:24:40.220 --> 00:24:43.840
of physical journey of Sarah
and trying to say alive

00:24:43.840 --> 00:24:49.630
as she begins to uncover
some of the causes

00:24:49.630 --> 00:24:52.330
for the disappearing girl
and her left is threatened.

00:24:52.330 --> 00:24:55.110
And then Emiliano is kind
of more like a moral journey

00:24:55.110 --> 00:24:58.530
in his sort of like the
temptations that happen

00:24:58.530 --> 00:25:05.630
when you're poor to try to
make money through drugs.

00:25:05.630 --> 00:25:12.050
And so, there was kind of
like both a physical journey

00:25:12.050 --> 00:25:13.580
and kind of a moral journey.

00:25:13.580 --> 00:25:16.170
And I think I needed, you
know, I needed two voices.

00:25:16.170 --> 00:25:19.590
And sometimes I think that like
the two characters are just part

00:25:19.590 --> 00:25:20.890
of myself.

00:25:20.890 --> 00:25:24.080
You know, Emiliano is who I am,
and Sarah is who I'd like to be.

00:25:24.080 --> 00:25:26.030
&gt;&gt; Linda Sue Park: Nice.

00:25:26.030 --> 00:25:27.330
All right.

