00:44:14.510 --> 00:44:19.050
But I'll just ask you to finish
by keeping in mind our theme

00:44:19.050 --> 00:44:20.450
of the power of books.

00:44:20.450 --> 00:44:24.450
You have an audience here of
readers and especially teachers

00:44:24.450 --> 00:44:27.290
and librarians who
work with young people.

00:44:27.290 --> 00:44:30.400
What one thing would you like
to tell them to take home

00:44:30.400 --> 00:44:34.390
to the young people about your
work or your particular book?

00:44:34.390 --> 00:44:35.860
Okay, Margarita.

00:44:35.860 --> 00:44:41.220
&gt;&gt; Margarita Engle: Just that
verse novels are interactive.

00:44:41.220 --> 00:44:45.590
The white space on
the page is not empty.

00:44:45.590 --> 00:44:51.410
It contains my emotions
and the reader's emotions,

00:44:51.410 --> 00:44:54.340
and you can invite students

00:44:54.340 --> 00:44:57.080
to write their own
poems in response.

00:44:57.080 --> 00:45:00.950
They can jump in at
any point on any page

00:45:00.950 --> 00:45:02.940
and write their own poems.

00:45:02.940 --> 00:45:05.160
They can write the
missing voices

00:45:05.160 --> 00:45:08.520
because I certainly
can't do it all.

00:45:08.520 --> 00:45:11.060
There's the old adage

00:45:11.060 --> 00:45:14.280
that a poem is never
finished; it's just abandoned.

00:45:14.280 --> 00:45:16.960
The same is true
of a poetry book.

00:45:16.960 --> 00:45:18.260
It's not finished.

00:45:18.260 --> 00:45:20.580
There's room for them
to come in and write.

00:45:20.580 --> 00:45:24.920
&gt;&gt; Mitali Perkins: Do
you want to go ahead?

00:45:24.920 --> 00:45:26.220
&gt;&gt; Francisco X. Stork: No.

00:45:26.220 --> 00:45:27.520
I'll go. You should be last.

00:45:27.520 --> 00:45:32.540
I think it's not about my books,
but I think the action item

00:45:32.540 --> 00:45:33.840
that I would say is

00:45:33.840 --> 00:45:37.290
to try mentor a young
person in your life.

00:45:37.290 --> 00:45:41.750
Just listen to their works.

00:45:41.750 --> 00:45:43.590
Help them along as best you can.

00:45:43.590 --> 00:45:47.410
And you don't have to
be a writing coach,

00:45:47.410 --> 00:45:50.720
but just one young
person that you find.

00:45:50.720 --> 00:45:52.020
&gt;&gt; Linda Sue Park: Yes.

00:45:52.020 --> 00:45:53.320
Jackie Woodson says she's trying

00:45:53.320 --> 00:45:54.670
to change the world
one reader at a time.

00:45:54.670 --> 00:45:55.970
&gt;&gt; Mitali Perkins: Yay.

00:45:55.970 --> 00:45:57.290
That's great.

00:45:57.290 --> 00:46:01.090
I'd say play around with
the windows and the mirrors.

00:46:01.090 --> 00:46:03.810
I found unexpected
mirrors in books,

00:46:03.810 --> 00:46:06.190
and so will the kids
that you serve.

00:46:06.190 --> 00:46:11.650
So I would say let kids roam
freely, but don't limit them

00:46:11.650 --> 00:46:14.690
to just the ethnic
or racial mirror

00:46:14.690 --> 00:46:16.710
because they're going
to find that.

00:46:16.710 --> 00:46:18.190
And I think play around with it

00:46:18.190 --> 00:46:20.040
in your collections
and your displays.

00:46:20.040 --> 00:46:23.840
So I would hate -- I heard
for many years in my career,

00:46:23.840 --> 00:46:27.560
we just don't have an Indian
population in our community,

00:46:27.560 --> 00:46:29.510
Mitali, and so that's why.

00:46:29.510 --> 00:46:31.030
So I don't hear that anymore.

00:46:31.030 --> 00:46:32.910
And I want to keep
that going forward

00:46:32.910 --> 00:46:34.880
because our books
are for all readers.

00:46:34.880 --> 00:46:36.430
And really, that's the --

00:46:36.430 --> 00:46:43.090
I am so thankful too
We Need Diverse Books.

00:46:43.090 --> 00:46:44.940
I mean, we've been writing
for years and years and years.

00:46:44.940 --> 00:46:49.040
And just to see the attraction
you guys have given our work

00:46:49.040 --> 00:46:50.380
because I don't hear
that anymore.

00:46:50.380 --> 00:46:53.450
And so, I'd say let your
young readers roam freely.

00:46:53.450 --> 00:46:54.750
Find the windows and mirrors,

00:46:54.750 --> 00:46:56.800
and just offer them
a feast of books.

00:46:56.800 --> 00:46:58.100
&gt;&gt; Francisco X. Stork:
There you go.

00:46:58.100 --> 00:46:59.400
Nice job.

