01:09:12.840 --> 01:09:15.420
We all know the adage if
a tree falls in the forest

01:09:15.420 --> 01:09:17.040
and no one is around to hear,
does it make a sound, right.

01:09:17.040 --> 01:09:18.410
We've all grown up hearing that.

01:09:18.410 --> 01:09:19.860
I'm not even sure if many
of us have ever thought

01:09:19.860 --> 01:09:21.270
about what exactly
is being said.

01:09:21.270 --> 01:09:22.650
But we hear that all the time.

01:09:22.650 --> 01:09:24.900
I've done some research on it
because I'm interested in it,

01:09:24.900 --> 01:09:26.550
and I think it's a
fascinating saying.

01:09:26.550 --> 01:09:28.260
And I've been digging around
trying figure out what

01:09:28.260 --> 01:09:30.130
that means for my life,
what that means for my work,

01:09:30.130 --> 01:09:31.820
what exactly are they
even talking about.

01:09:31.820 --> 01:09:35.550
Turns out that thought it is
a philosophical statement,

01:09:35.550 --> 01:09:37.500
it actually was a
scientific statement.

01:09:37.500 --> 01:09:40.620
And scientists were saying
basically that if a tree falls

01:09:40.620 --> 01:09:43.280
in the forest, what happens
when it come to sound is

01:09:43.280 --> 01:09:44.580
that the tree hits the ground.

01:09:44.580 --> 01:09:45.880
There's a vibration
from that impact,

01:09:45.880 --> 01:09:48.690
and that vibration then
somehow travels to --

01:09:48.690 --> 01:09:55.040
Y'all didn't make the
announcement [laughter]?

01:09:55.040 --> 01:09:58.480
Exactly. The tree falls,
hits the ground, all right.

01:09:58.480 --> 01:09:59.780
There's a vibration.

01:09:59.780 --> 01:10:01.080
That vibration travels
to the eardrum.

01:10:01.080 --> 01:10:02.380
And then when it
hits the eardrum,

01:10:02.380 --> 01:10:03.680
the eardrum makes the sound.

01:10:03.680 --> 01:10:05.660
But if the vibration does not
hit the eardrum, technically,

01:10:05.660 --> 01:10:06.960
then the sound is not made.

01:10:06.960 --> 01:10:08.260
That's how sound works, right.

01:10:08.260 --> 01:10:10.490
So the scientists were saying
if a tree hits the ground

01:10:10.490 --> 01:10:11.790
and no one is there to hear it,

01:10:11.790 --> 01:10:13.600
technically it does
not make a sound.

01:10:13.600 --> 01:10:19.100
of course, for me, that is --
I mean, it makes sense sort of,

01:10:19.100 --> 01:10:21.540
except for the fact that I
think somehow in that argument,

01:10:21.540 --> 01:10:24.850
it sort of disqualifies the
idea of the vibration being made

01:10:24.850 --> 01:10:26.150
in the first place, right.

01:10:26.150 --> 01:10:28.460
So if a tree is a piece of
matter, a tree is a thing,

01:10:28.460 --> 01:10:31.020
it's a living thing, a breathing
thing, a growing thing,

01:10:31.020 --> 01:10:32.420
once that tree hits the ground,

01:10:32.420 --> 01:10:34.720
there's a vibration made whether
someone is there to hear it

01:10:34.720 --> 01:10:36.950
or not is of less
importance than the fact

01:10:36.950 --> 01:10:39.150
that the vibration is made
and to not acknowledge

01:10:39.150 --> 01:10:41.910
that vibration is to
disqualify that life

01:10:41.910 --> 01:10:43.670
and the falling of said tree.

01:10:43.670 --> 01:10:45.510
Now from a philosophical --

01:10:45.510 --> 01:10:49.520
[ Applause ]

01:10:49.520 --> 01:10:52.660
Now from the philosophical,
from a philosophical standpoint,

01:10:52.660 --> 01:10:53.960
right, which is the
other argument,

01:10:53.960 --> 01:10:55.390
which is the colloquial
argument that most of make

01:10:55.390 --> 01:10:56.690
when we say this, right.

01:10:56.690 --> 01:10:58.680
If a tree falls in the forest
and no one is around to hear it,

01:10:58.680 --> 01:11:00.230
does it make a sound,
and we look at that

01:11:00.230 --> 01:11:02.570
as a philosophical
statement, right.

01:11:02.570 --> 01:11:04.850
From a philosophical standpoint,

01:11:04.850 --> 01:11:09.940
I think that perhaps we're not
necessarily asking the right

01:11:09.940 --> 01:11:11.240
questions, right.

01:11:11.240 --> 01:11:13.210
It's like that seems like just
a limited and simplified sort

01:11:13.210 --> 01:11:16.270
of question to be asking about
a tree that falls in a forest

01:11:16.270 --> 01:11:17.820
with no one around to hear it,

01:11:17.820 --> 01:11:20.230
because there are other
questions, extenuating questions

01:11:20.230 --> 01:11:21.980
that we should be
asking ourselves

01:11:21.980 --> 01:11:25.280
to better understand the context
in which a tree is falling

01:11:25.280 --> 01:11:27.910
in a forest with no
one around to hear it.

01:11:27.910 --> 01:11:30.470
For instance, is
the wind blowing?

01:11:30.470 --> 01:11:32.770
For instance, was the
tree struck by lightning?

01:11:32.770 --> 01:11:35.710
For instance, is there something
eating at the base of the tree,

01:11:35.710 --> 01:11:37.350
which makes it a
little less strong?

01:11:37.350 --> 01:11:40.240
For instance, are there
termites eating the tree

01:11:40.240 --> 01:11:41.540
from the inside out?

01:11:41.540 --> 01:11:44.710
All of this would help us try
to better understand whether

01:11:44.710 --> 01:11:48.910
or not it matters that
if a sound is made or not

01:11:48.910 --> 01:11:52.500
if a tree falls in a forest
with no one there to hear it.

01:11:52.500 --> 01:11:56.310
Now let's transpose
tree for child, right.

01:11:56.310 --> 01:12:00.250
From a scientific standpoint,
from a scientific standpoint,

01:12:00.250 --> 01:12:02.720
if a child falls
and no one is there

01:12:02.720 --> 01:12:04.910
to hear it, does
it make a sound?

01:12:04.910 --> 01:12:07.590
According to the scientists,
the child does not, right.

01:12:07.590 --> 01:12:09.070
According to what
I'm arguing, thought,

01:12:09.070 --> 01:12:12.170
is if we say the child
does not make a sound,

01:12:12.170 --> 01:12:13.870
if we say that the
child's impact

01:12:13.870 --> 01:12:15.870
on that ground does
not create a vibration,

01:12:15.870 --> 01:12:20.240
then we disqualify the
life of said child, right.

01:12:20.240 --> 01:12:22.440
Now from a philosophical
standpoint,

01:12:22.440 --> 01:12:24.580
if a child falls,
does it make a sound?

01:12:24.580 --> 01:12:28.120
Again, I think we need
to ask more questions.

01:12:28.120 --> 01:12:31.630
Number one, was there
wind blowing?

01:12:31.630 --> 01:12:34.020
Was there something
there pushing the child?

01:12:34.020 --> 01:12:35.820
Was there something
there, a force,

01:12:35.820 --> 01:12:38.600
an unseen force forcing
the child down?

01:12:38.600 --> 01:12:41.930
Was there something there eating
at the child's base, right?

01:12:41.930 --> 01:12:44.630
Something there that maybe we
don't know eating at the child.

01:12:44.630 --> 01:12:46.530
Were there termites involved,

01:12:46.530 --> 01:12:48.370
eating the child
from the inside out?

01:12:48.370 --> 01:12:50.820
Was lightening striking
any way in the vicinity?

01:12:50.820 --> 01:12:52.550
Was anything on fire?

01:12:52.550 --> 01:12:55.700
Was the ground weakened
by anything, right?

01:12:55.700 --> 01:13:02.340
And lastly, lastly,
why aren't anyone --

01:13:02.340 --> 01:13:05.430
Like, where are the
people, right?

01:13:05.430 --> 01:13:07.470
If a tree falls in the forest

01:13:07.470 --> 01:13:09.490
and no one is around,
does it make a sound?

01:13:09.490 --> 01:13:12.920
the question is, why
is no one around?

01:13:12.920 --> 01:13:14.220
Where are the people?

01:13:14.220 --> 01:13:16.280
Where is everyone, right?

01:13:16.280 --> 01:13:18.380
Because that's the question
that we should be asking,

01:13:18.380 --> 01:13:21.360
and that is what long way
down is actually about, right.

01:13:21.360 --> 01:13:23.700
Everyone is saying like, oh,
it's about a kid and a gun.

01:13:23.700 --> 01:13:25.000
No, no, no, no, no.

01:13:25.000 --> 01:13:27.350
This is about acknowledging
the fact that the kids

01:13:27.350 --> 01:13:30.370
