If this proverb, a book is a
garden carried in a pocket,

01:18:33.000 --> 01:18:37.510
is true, then Arturo Alfonso
Schomburg, the historian

01:18:37.510 --> 01:18:42.810
and book collector, had a green
thumb and a harvest of pride.

01:18:42.810 --> 01:18:46.090
There was no field of human
endeavor that he did not till

01:18:46.090 --> 01:18:49.780
with his determined hand, that
he did not sow with the seeds

01:18:49.780 --> 01:18:53.270
of curiosity, where he
did not weed out truths,

01:18:53.270 --> 01:18:56.310
lies and half-truths,
or that he did not water

01:18:56.310 --> 01:19:00.480
with a growing sense of
African awareness and heritage.

01:19:00.480 --> 01:19:03.560
If a book is a garden
carried in a pocket,

01:19:03.560 --> 01:19:06.490
then Schomburg yielded
a bumper crop,

01:19:06.490 --> 01:19:10.940
blanketed Mount Kilimanjaro
with African violets.

01:19:10.940 --> 01:19:15.940
If I had African
violets this morning,

01:19:15.940 --> 01:19:19.640
I would certainly give some
to We Need Diverse Books,

01:19:19.640 --> 01:19:26.420
to the judges, to my editor,
Hilary Van Dusen, my agent,

01:19:26.420 --> 01:19:30.010
Rubin Pfeffer, to my family
and friends who are here

01:19:30.010 --> 01:19:33.430
with me today, to all of
the librarians and educators

01:19:33.430 --> 01:19:38.050
who use my books and other
diverse books in classrooms,

01:19:38.050 --> 01:19:42.760
to last but not least,
my frequent collaborator,

01:19:42.760 --> 01:19:47.850
Eric Velasquez, who
pitched this project to me.

01:19:47.850 --> 01:19:52.160
Schomburg, in several ways,
brings my book full circle,

01:19:52.160 --> 01:19:54.820
as does this award ceremony.

01:19:54.820 --> 01:19:57.680
Just as Schomburg experienced
a slight at the hands

01:19:57.680 --> 01:20:00.020
of his fifth-grade
teacher who told him

01:20:00.020 --> 01:20:03.540
that African descendants
had no history worth noting,

01:20:03.540 --> 01:20:06.960
I was dissed by an
eighth-grade teacher.

01:20:06.960 --> 01:20:08.600
Fascinated with the
Harlem Renaissance,

01:20:08.600 --> 01:20:11.430
I wrote a research
paper on Countee Cullen

01:20:11.430 --> 01:20:14.040
after having read
his poem Incident.

01:20:14.040 --> 01:20:18.230
I was one of only four black
students at my grade level,

01:20:18.230 --> 01:20:21.220
at an exclusive Quaker
school in Baltimore.

01:20:21.220 --> 01:20:23.230
And I was the only
one of those four

01:20:23.230 --> 01:20:26.090
who had transferred
from public school.

01:20:26.090 --> 01:20:29.110
When I got my paper back,
the teacher had given me a B,

01:20:29.110 --> 01:20:34.140
and it offered but one
comment: did you write this.

01:20:34.140 --> 01:20:37.770
Obviously, he had
expected less of me.

01:20:37.770 --> 01:20:41.160
Ever since, I have
strived to use my pen

01:20:41.160 --> 01:20:43.020
to affirm my heritage
and culture.

01:20:43.020 --> 01:20:46.400
When I was an aspiring
children's book writer,

01:20:46.400 --> 01:20:49.530
before I had anything
published but adult poetry,

01:20:49.530 --> 01:20:52.740
I studied the work
of Walter Dean Myers.

01:20:52.740 --> 01:20:56.910
Among the mentor text that
I turned to were Brown Baby,

01:20:56.910 --> 01:21:00.820
I'm sorry, Brown Angels,
Angel to Angel, Harlem,

01:21:00.820 --> 01:21:03.580
and One More River to Cross.

01:21:03.580 --> 01:21:07.660
When I was in graduate school, I
worked on a photo essay project

01:21:07.660 --> 01:21:11.830
that evolved into a children's
book, many years later.

01:21:11.830 --> 01:21:14.380
It took 20 years to be exact.

01:21:14.380 --> 01:21:17.860
My picture research took
me to the Schomburg Center,

01:21:17.860 --> 01:21:21.200
to Moorland-Spingarn Research
Center at Howard University,

01:21:21.200 --> 01:21:23.880
and to the Library
of Congress prints

01:21:23.880 --> 01:21:26.710
and photographs department,
in this very building.

01:21:26.710 --> 01:21:30.160
I was looking for images
to accompany my poems.

01:21:30.160 --> 01:21:33.520
Instead, I found pictures
that begged for words.

01:21:33.520 --> 01:21:35.450
Some were of historic figures.

01:21:35.450 --> 01:21:39.300
Others were of everyday people
whose names have been lost.

01:21:39.300 --> 01:21:42.230
I wrote poems to
give them voices.

01:21:42.230 --> 01:21:46.730
I began right then and there
collecting images and stories.

01:21:46.730 --> 01:21:51.810
I'm going to close with a poem
from that book that first led me

01:21:51.810 --> 01:21:55.920
to the Schomburg Center:
Remember the Bridge.

01:21:55.920 --> 01:21:58.780
Remember the bridge that
your ancestors crossed,

01:21:58.780 --> 01:22:01.940
the sweat that was spilled
and the lives that were lost.

01:22:01.940 --> 01:22:04.120
Remember the slaves
who raised corn

01:22:04.120 --> 01:22:06.640
and cotton keep singing
their songs

01:22:06.640 --> 01:22:10.090
so they won't be forgotten, the
Underground Railroad that passed

01:22:10.090 --> 01:22:12.710
through at night, the
signs and conductors

01:22:12.710 --> 01:22:14.830
that guided slaves' flight.

01:22:14.830 --> 01:22:17.700
Remember the soldiers who fought
though they knew they might not

01:22:17.700 --> 01:22:20.210
be free when the
battle was through.

01:22:20.210 --> 01:22:24.960
Remember the old souls who
handed down tales, the bold men

01:22:24.960 --> 01:22:28.920
and women who blazed their
own trails from the South

01:22:28.920 --> 01:22:32.520
to the North, from farm
to big-city, with satchels

01:22:32.520 --> 01:22:35.220
of dreams and no use for pity.

01:22:35.220 --> 01:22:38.680
Remember the bootblacks
who made old shoes shine,

01:22:38.680 --> 01:22:42.130
the industrious laborers
who manned factory lines.

01:22:42.130 --> 01:22:45.360
Remember the housemaids
who scrubbed dirty floors,

01:22:45.360 --> 01:22:48.650
the leaders who spoke
out to open closed doors.

01:22:48.650 --> 01:22:51.800
Remember the hard way
the ancestors came,

01:22:51.800 --> 01:22:55.940
snatched from the motherland
bound in iron chains.

01:22:55.940 --> 01:22:59.540
Remember the voyage,
the capture, the chase,

01:22:59.540 --> 01:23:03.540
young warriors who vanished
without even a trace.

01:23:03.540 --> 01:23:07.310
Remember the ocean much too
vast to span, long shadows

01:23:07.310 --> 01:23:09.880
on shorelines and
footprints in sand.

01:23:09.880 --> 01:23:13.190
Forget not the glory of Africa's
past, the temples and riches

01:23:13.190 --> 01:23:17.660
that to this day last,
bronze baskets and mud cloth,

01:23:17.660 --> 01:23:22.400
pyramids of stone, ebony
statues and bracelets of bone.

01:23:22.400 --> 01:23:24.090
The journey continues.

01:23:24.090 --> 01:23:26.620
The bridge still holds strong.

01:23:26.620 --> 01:23:28.570
Hands reach across water.

01:23:28.570 --> 01:23:30.680
Hearts sing a new song.

01:23:30.680 --> 01:23:32.480
Thank you.

01:23:32.480 --> 01:23:52.010
[ Applause ]

01:23:52.010 --> 01:23:53.310
&gt;&gt; Jacqueline Woodson:

01:23:53.310 --> 01:23:54.670
That posing for the picture
