01:28:26.430 --> 01:28:29.200
You truly outdid
yourself with this one,

01:28:29.200 --> 01:28:31.390
our fifth collaboration.

01:28:31.390 --> 01:28:36.860
I want to thank the love of
my life, Elizabeth Rosario,

01:28:36.860 --> 01:28:41.690
not only for posing as
Elizabeth and Phillis Wheatley,

01:28:41.690 --> 01:28:45.420
but also for the
love and support,

01:28:45.420 --> 01:28:47.650
reassurance and strength.

01:28:47.650 --> 01:28:49.510
You are my rock.

01:28:49.510 --> 01:28:56.360
[ Applause ]

01:28:56.360 --> 01:28:58.750
Okay. I first became aware

01:28:58.750 --> 01:29:03.670
of Arturo Alfonso
Schomburg in the third grade.

01:29:03.670 --> 01:29:08.210
My teacher, Ms. Holmes, kept
a poster of Arturo Schomburg

01:29:08.210 --> 01:29:11.120
on her classroom wall,
along with posters

01:29:11.120 --> 01:29:15.290
of Martin Luther King Jr.,
Malcom X and Marcus Garvey,

01:29:15.290 --> 01:29:17.780
that Marcus Garvey
poster with the cute,

01:29:17.780 --> 01:29:19.610
the really cool, you know.

01:29:19.610 --> 01:29:23.070
He had the uniform
with the -- Yeah.

01:29:23.070 --> 01:29:29.430
But what a gift the day she
said to me that Arturo Schomburg

01:29:29.430 --> 01:29:32.320
and I shared something
in common,

01:29:32.320 --> 01:29:35.450
that we both had
roots in Puerto Rico.

01:29:35.450 --> 01:29:39.950
And as she continued with a
brief talk on Arturo Schomburg,

01:29:39.950 --> 01:29:44.220
for the first time in my life, I
found a hero that looked like me

01:29:44.220 --> 01:29:46.250
and that I can identify with.

01:29:46.250 --> 01:29:49.740
I could not wait to get
home and ask my grandma

01:29:49.740 --> 01:29:53.380
if she knew this great man
responsible for the library

01:29:53.380 --> 01:29:55.640
on 135th Street in Harlem.

01:29:55.640 --> 01:29:59.810
[Foreign language
spoken], I asked thinking

01:29:59.810 --> 01:30:08.930
that I would just throw
her off with the name.

01:30:08.930 --> 01:30:10.230
[Foreign language spoken].

01:30:10.230 --> 01:30:12.510
Of course, that man
was a genius.

01:30:12.510 --> 01:30:19.090
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

01:30:19.090 --> 01:30:22.250
The same place we come from.

01:30:22.250 --> 01:30:24.830
However, aside from
Schomburg's collection of books

01:30:24.830 --> 01:30:31.040
and artifacts, she didn't
know much more about the man;

01:30:31.040 --> 01:30:33.860
37 years later, while

01:30:33.860 --> 01:30:36.390
at the Schomburg Center
attending a performance

01:30:36.390 --> 01:30:38.750
of the last poets with Elizabeth

01:30:38.750 --> 01:30:42.590
and her good friend Sheena
[assumed spelling], Sheena turns

01:30:42.590 --> 01:30:44.560
to me and says, you know,

01:30:44.560 --> 01:30:47.690
there are no children's
books on Arturo Schomburg.

01:30:47.690 --> 01:30:51.560
You know, you ought to
think about doing that book.

01:30:53.100 --> 01:30:57.190
Suddenly, I realized that
this was the handsome man

01:30:57.190 --> 01:31:01.260
in that poster that I would
stare at day after day

01:31:01.260 --> 01:31:05.910
in third grade, that genius that
my grandmother talked about.

01:31:05.910 --> 01:31:07.860
Wait, wait.

01:31:07.860 --> 01:31:12.470
I contacted Carol
immediately and asked her

01:31:12.470 --> 01:31:15.000
to write me a manuscript
on Schomburg.

01:31:15.000 --> 01:31:20.160
That was 2006.

01:31:20.160 --> 01:31:23.400
We submitted the project to
several publishing houses

01:31:23.400 --> 01:31:27.170
and we were rejected everywhere.

01:31:28.810 --> 01:31:33.270
This is just a story about
a man who collected books.

01:31:33.270 --> 01:31:34.600
He's so boring.

01:31:34.600 --> 01:31:38.180
Jazz him up a little
bit, you know.

01:31:38.180 --> 01:31:41.430
Well, it didn't happen then.

01:31:41.430 --> 01:31:45.590
In 2014, our now
agent, Rubin Pfeffer,

01:31:45.590 --> 01:31:48.030
decided to give it another try.

01:31:48.030 --> 01:31:53.780
And after a lot of work, a new
manuscript and new sketches,

01:31:53.780 --> 01:31:56.190
Schomburg, the man
who built a library,

01:31:56.190 --> 01:31:59.310
found a home at Candlewick
Press.

01:31:59.310 --> 01:32:01.390
What a journey.

01:32:01.390 --> 01:32:04.680
However, it was through
Carol's brilliant words

01:32:04.680 --> 01:32:08.010
that I truly discovered
Schomburg's genius

01:32:08.010 --> 01:32:10.540
and his gift to all of us.

01:32:10.540 --> 01:32:14.030
This project has changed
my life in so many ways.

01:32:14.030 --> 01:32:20.250
I even ended up in the
hospital, didn't I.

01:32:20.250 --> 01:32:23.330
I've even met Dean Schomburg,

01:32:23.330 --> 01:32:25.620
which is Arturo Schomburg's
grandson,

01:32:25.620 --> 01:32:28.170
who is now a man in his 70s.

01:32:28.170 --> 01:32:31.490
I've met his daughter
her son Miles.

01:32:31.490 --> 01:32:36.120
So that's Schomburg's
great, great grandson.

01:32:36.120 --> 01:32:43.510
And so, I conclude with to
Arturo Alfonso Schomburg, I say,

01:32:43.510 --> 01:32:49.510
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

01:32:49.510 --> 01:33:13.130
[ Applause ]

01:33:13.130 --> 01:33:14.430
&gt;&gt; Jacqueline Woodson: Oh, okay.

01:33:14.430 --> 01:33:22.510
Awesome. Na na na na na to
the publishers that said no.

01:33:22.510 --> 01:33:31.940
[ Laughter ]

01:33:31.940 --> 01:33:35.380
Man, I bet you you'll look quite
hard at the next book that comes

01:33:35.380 --> 01:33:41.530
across your -- So now
it is my great pleasure

01:33:41.530 --> 01:33:43.730
to present the Honor awards.

01:33:43.730 --> 01:33:46.490
And I don't have
any bios for them.

01:33:46.490 --> 01:33:50.750
So we're just going to roll
with this for the authors.

01:33:50.750 --> 01:33:53.510
Caroline, what.

